inferior hypogastric plexus","Direct branches from the lumbar sympathetic chain","Branches from the pudendal nerve","Branches from the sacral plexus","Direct branches from the vagus nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe uterus primarily receives innervation from \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranches from the inferior hypogastric plexus\u003C/strong\u003E. This plexus (sometimes called the pelvic plexus) contains sympathetic fibers from the superior hypogastric plexus, parasympathetic fibers from the pelvic splanchnic nerves (S2-S4), and sensory afferents. These nerves regulate uterine smooth muscle contraction, blood flow, and transmit pain signals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the sacral plexus\u003C/strong\u003E - The sacral plexus primarily provides somatic innervation to the lower limb and perineum, not direct visceral innervation to the uterus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect branches from the vagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The vagus nerve provides parasympathetic innervation to abdominal organs but does not extend to pelvic organs like the uterus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect branches from the lumbar sympathetic chain\u003C/strong\u003E - While sympathetic fibers originate from the lumbar sympathetic chain, they first travel through the superior hypogastric plexus before reaching the inferior hypogastric plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches from the pudendal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The pudendal nerve provides somatic innervation to the external genitalia and perineum, not the uterus\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the innervation of the uterus is important for procedures such as hysterectomy, where damage to these nerves can affect bladder function and sexual response. It also explains the complex nature of pelvic pain, which can be referred to different regions due to shared innervation pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The uterus receives innervation from the inferior hypogastric plexus, which contains sympathetic, parasympathetic, and sensory nerve fibers.","The inferior hypogastric plexus is formed by contributions from the superior hypogastric plexus and pelvic splanchnic nerves.","Pelvic viscera receive autonomic innervation that regulates smooth muscle contraction, glandular secretion, and transmits sensory information."],"references":["McMinn RMH, Hutchings RT. Last\u0027s Anatomy: Regional and Applied. 12th ed. Edinburgh: Churchill Livingstone Elsevier; 2011."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82961"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21342"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82961"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-26T11:16:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T11:17:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14215"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100544"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"